  "text_content": "LIVE 7:30 a.m. EDT (2330 UTC) Roscosmos Progress 94 Launch coverage of the Roscosmos Progress 94 cargo spacecraft from Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan to the International Space Station Artemis II The first crewed Artemis flight marks a key step toward long‑term return to the Moon and future missions to Mars. Forging New Frontiers MISSION UPDATES Artemis Blog behind the scenes Artemis II Podcast NASA+ original series Moonbound Featured News Recently Published Blog 2 Min Read NASA’s Artemis II Rocket Arrives at Launch Pad 39B News Release 2 Min Read NASA to Cover Progress 94 Spacecraft Launch, Space Station Docking Article 2 Min Read NASA Exploration, Science Inspire “Project Hail Mary” Film Blog 3 Min Read Week Wraps with Health Research and Spacewalk Closeout Procedures 4 Min Read Meet the Platypi: NASA’s Newest Astronaut Candidate Class Article 3 Min Read NASA Laser Reflecting Instrument Makes GPS Satellite More Accurate Article 5 Min Read NASA’s Hubble Unexpectedly Catches Comet Breaking Up Article 3 Min Read What’s Up: March 2026 Skywatching Tips from NASA Article How Open Data Captured 3I/ATLAS Comet 3I/ATLAS will soon leave our solar system forever, but the data collected about it will remain available in NASA’s public archives. More than a dozen NASA missions observed the comet, which is only the third identified object to visit our solar system from interstellar space. Learn More about How Open Data Captured 3I/ATLAS NASA Science Discover More Asteroids, Comets & Meteors Hubble Space Telescope James Webb Space Telescope Eyes Today Image Of The Day Smiles and Spacesuits NASA astronaut and Expedition 74 crew member Chris Williams smiles for the camera during a spacesuit fit verification inside the International Space Station’s Quest airlock. Browse Image Archive Today Image Of The Day View image Image Galleries More NASA Images NASA Spacewalkers Gallery 24 Images Astronaut Selfies Gallery 20 Images Views From The Cupola Gallery 20 Images Explore the Universe from your Inbox Stay up-to-date on the latest news from NASA–from Earth to the Moon, the Solar System and beyond. We will never share your email address. Privacy Policy Sign Up Freedom 250 NASA Celebrates America’s 250th Birthday Our spirit of adventure and innovation will raise our nation to new heights. From the earliest days of exploration, to the first steps on the Moon and the missions shaping our future, NASA represents the spirit of discovery that defines our nation. As the United States approaches its semiquincentennial, Freedom 250 highlights how innovation, courage, and scientific leadership have carried America forward — and how NASA continues to expand the frontier for the next generation. Learn More about NASA Celebrates America’s 250th Birthday NASA astronaut Jonnny Kim poses for a portrait with the American flag on the Fourth of July, or Independence Day, inside the International Space Station’s “window to the world,” the cupola. NASA More Topics from NASA Missions Humans In Space Earth Our Solar System Universe Science Missions Aeronautics Technology",
